SP  - 939
EP  - 961
VL  - 56
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12127
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Using a simple, multisector model of endogenous growth, we show that commodity-specific consumption externalities can be a source of structural change. When the degrees of consumption externalities are different between goods, each sector grows at a different rate. However, the aggregate economy exhibits balanced growth in that capital stock and expenditure grow at the same constant rate. A three-sector version of our model may reconcile Kaldor's stylized facts with empirically plausible profiles of industrial structure transformation.
ER  - 

